      <img loading="lazy" decoding="async" src="https://apedraza.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Screenshot-2024-12-12-at-23-37-48-MoSCoW-Prioritisation-Trello.png" alt="MoSCoW Prioritization">
      <figcaption>MoSCoW Prioritization</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>Finally, we shared it with the rest of stakeholders for the project and started working on these items by priority.</p>
  </section>
  
  <section>
    <h2>Defining and developing iteratively</h2>
    <p>We started with the <strong>low hanging fruit</strong>. The <strong>biggest drop-off point</strong> of out flow was at the very beginning:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>The marketing page where users are meant to learn about job posting was dull and outdated.</li>
      <li>It had a 3 steps main CTA intended to make users feel invested in the task by the time they arrived at the main form, but that in most cases had to be refilled a second time.</li>
      <li>The actual information was below the fold, and by the time users reached it, we had already lost 30% of our page viewers.</li>
    </ul>
    <figure class="img__full-width">
      <img loading="lazy" decoding="async" src="https://apedraza.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/posting-options-1.png" alt="Comparative between old and new marketing page">
      <figcaption>Comparative between old and new marketing page</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>While I was working on the redesign, the development team took some time into fixing already identified bugs from the process that needed to be fixed independently of the redesign and I also aligned with the marketing stakeholders to <strong>review the communications</strong> users encountered throughout the job posting process.</p>
    <p>Then we got into the main course:</p>
    <p>Our <strong>job form</strong> was one single page. It was huge and daunting for any unsuspecting recruiter, so I propose to split it <strong>into manageable bits</strong> to improve the experience.</p>
    <p>I started working on an iterative proposal of different flows to move from the current one step form into a three step one that would structure the date in a more contextual way and make it more digestible.</p>
    <p>Given the technology with which the old job posting form was built, it was impossible to modify the flow in smaller steps without introducing technical debt into the system. Because of that, we decided to develop the version of the form that included the <strong>major number of changes in the job posting flow but wouldn't imply working in other sections</strong> of the site.</p>
