      <figcaption>New flow definition</figcaption>
    </figure>
  </section>
  
  <section>
    <h2>Delivery</h2>
    <p>It took about 4 months to fully migrate and split the job posting flow. The process was long and tedious, but it included many other changes that aimed to <strong>give users more control</strong> over their job posting experience and <strong>increased the data integrity</strong> that Devex has about their users. In the end, we thrived.</p>
  </section>
  
  <section>
    <h2>Impact and further work</h2>
    <p>The new version of Devex job posting process was released early November 2024. The changes in the communications, the marketing page and other small changes have been in production since October 2024. In that time:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>The <strong>engagement</strong> within the job posting form <strong>increased by 28%</strong>, although drop-off levels in the registration step were quite high.</li>
      <li>The percentage of users who visited the marketing page and <strong>started a job posting</strong> process <strong>increased by 6%</strong>.</li>
      <li>The number of people who inquiried about <strong>job bundles</strong> from the jobs marketing page <strong>tripled</strong> in the first month. </li>
      <li>Roughly 70% of our recruiter accounts were held by USAID contractors. Up to the moment Donald Trump ordered USAID freeze in <strong>February 2025</strong>, the job posting flow was recording its <strong>best numbers of the last 6 months</strong>.</li>
      <li>There were several <strong>pending changes</strong> aiming to improve the <strong>quality of the options</strong> in the form (clearer and new values) and <strong>simplify it further</strong> (automatize organization information step). </li>
    </ul>
  </section>
